"Quick jump" is the art of moving between your most-used projects without typing cd ~/Documents/work/projects/client-a/src.

Since you hate "bollox with flags," the goal is to get where you need to go in 2 or 3 keystrokes. Here are the two best ways to do it:

Option 1: The "Smart CD" (The Z-Jump)
The most popular tool for this is zoxide (or its predecessor z). It remembers where you've been and weights directories by "frecency" (frequency + recency).

Install it: brew install zoxide (or sudo apt install zoxide).

Add to bashrc: eval "$(zoxide init bash)".

The Magic: You don't type paths anymore.

If you once went to ~/code/personal/webapp-frontend, you now just type:

z web (It jumps there instantly).

z front (It jumps there instantly).

Option 2: The "Manual Jump" (The j Function)
If you don't want to install a new tool and prefer to explicitly "mark" your favorite spots, use this snippet in your .bashrc. It uses a hidden file to store your shortcuts.

Bash
# Quick Jump Function
# Usage: 
#   mark myproject  (saves current dir as 'myproject')
#   j myproject     (jumps there from anywhere)
#   j --list        (shows all marks)

mark() {
  mkdir -p ~/.marks
  ln -s "$(pwd)" "$HOME/.marks/$1"
}

j() {
  if [ "$1" = "--list" ]; then
    ls -l ~/.marks | awk '{print $9 " -> " $11}'
    return
  fi
  cd -P "$HOME/.marks/$1" 2>/dev/null || echo "Mark '$1' not found. Use 'mark <name>' first."
}
Option 3: The "Telescope" (CD with Search)
If you can't remember what a folder is called, combine cd with a fuzzy finder like fzf. This is the ultimate "low-effort" navigation.

Bash
# Requires 'fzf' installed
# Usage: cdf (then just start typing any part of the folder name)
cdf() {
  local dir
  dir=$(find ${1:-.} -path '*/.*' -prune -o -type d -print 2> /dev/null | fzf +m) && cd "$dir"
}
