Gemini said
It feels fragile because it’s a fuzzy trigger. It’s not a standard Bash feature; it’s a helper script provided by fzf.

How it works
The Trigger: You type ** followed by TAB.

The Context: fzf looks at the command before the stars.

If you type cd **<TAB>, it only shows directories.

If you type vim **<TAB>, it shows all files.

If you type ssh **<TAB>, it pulls from your ~/.ssh/config or /etc/hosts.

Why it feels "fragile"
Recursive lag: By default, it tries to find everything from your current spot down. If you're in your home directory, it might hang while it indexes your entire drive.

Hidden junk: It often gets cluttered with .git, node_modules, or cache files, making the list uselessly long.

The "No-Bollox" Fix
To make it robust and fast, you need to tell fzf to stop looking at trash. Add this to your .bashrc:

Bash
# Force fzf to use 'find' but skip hidden/junk folders
export FZF_DEFAULT_COMMAND='find . -path "*/.*" -prune -o -type f -print -o -type d -print'

# Apply the same logic specifically to the ** trigger
_fzf_compgen_path() {
  find "$1" -path '*/.*' -prune -o -print
}

_fzf_compgen_dir() {
  find "$1" -path '*/.*' -prune -o -type d -print
}
Better Alternative: ALT-C
