Gemini said
Git doesn't have a single "global" smart case toggle like Vim, but you can enable it for the specific commands where it actually matters (searching and completion).

Here is how to get "Smart Case" (ignore case unless an uppercase letter is typed) for your Git workflow:

1. Smart Case for git grep
This is the most useful one. If you search for git grep "user", it finds everything; if you search for git grep "User", it becomes case-sensitive.

Add this to your .bashrc:

Bash
git config --global grep.ignoreCase true
git config --global grep.extendedRegexp true
Note: Git's internal "ignoreCase" is actually "smart" in newer versions when combined with certain flags, but for a truly "bollox-free" experience, most people just alias it:

Bash
alias gg='git grep -i' # Force ignore case for speed
2. Smart Case for Git Tab-Completion
If you type git checkout feat<TAB> and your branch is named Feature-Login, Bash usually fails. To make Git completion case-insensitive, add this to your ~/.inputrc file (not your bashrc):

Bash
set completion-ignore-case on
set show-all-if-ambidextrous on
3. Smart Case for git log
If you want to search commit messages without worrying about caps:

Bash
git config --global i18n.logOutputEncoding utf-8
alias gls='git log --all --grep' # Then use -i manually when needed
The "No-Bollox" Summary
If you want your entire terminal to behave with Smart Case (including grep, fzf, and git), the most effective setup is actually through fzf variables in your .bashrc, because fzf is smart-case by default:

Bash
# This makes all your fzf-based git searching smart-case
